This paper is primarily focused on modeling human conversation using neural dialog systems, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also discusses incorporating personalization into dialog systems, which involves machine learning techniques such as multi-task learning and feature sharing. This suggests that the paper could also be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper analyzes the shortcomings of an existing dialog system and proposes modifications to the architecture, which could fall under the sub-category of cs.SD (Software Engineering). Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of personalized dialog systems in human-computer interaction, which could be relevant to the sub-category of cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction).
